<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-158-562  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 158 562.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  March 27 1989 n213 p15(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GE brings software to life. (General Electric's Scisor retrievalsystem)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Puttre, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>General Electric Research and Development Center has announced anewly-developed system called Scisor (System for ConceptualInformation Summarization, Organization, and Retrieval) that canhandle a large input-output of information.andP;  Scisor usesartificial intelligence, natural language, and database managementto cut through the Dow Jones wire services in order to collectrelevant financial data.andP;  The prototype system actually locateskey words and 'reads' them before deciding to keep or discardthem.andP;  The system will remain in development for another yearbefore a marketing outlet is sought for it.andP;  Scisor runs on Unixworkstations and any computer that can run Common Lisp, Theprogram has been successfully ported to VMS and VAX environments.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   General Electric Co. (product development).andO;Product:   Scisor (Information retrieval system) (product development).andO;Topic:     Information Storage and RetrievalData Manipulation LanguagesProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>